PROJECT 8: CloudWatch Monitoring + Alerts
Date: Day 11
What I built:

Created custom CloudWatch dashboard (dipesh-security-dashboard)
Added EC2 CPU utilization line chart widget to dashboard
Added S3 bucket size number widget to dashboard
Created billing alarm alerting when charges exceed $5
Created EC2 status check alarm for instance health monitoring
Created CloudTrail log metric filter for console login detection
Ran CloudWatch Logs Insights query on CloudTrail logs
Uploaded index.html to S3 bucket for CloudFront preparation
Connected all alarms to SNS topic for email notifications

Security concepts applied:

Billing alarm prevents unexpected charge surprises
EC2 status check alarm detects instance failures immediately
Console login metric filter detects unauthorized access attempts
CloudWatch Logs Insights enables security log analysis
Centralized dashboard gives single pane of glass monitoring
All alerts connected to SNS for real time notification

Challenges faced and resolved:

Billing metric not found in CloudWatch select metric
Enabled billing alerts in Billing Preferences first
Billing metric appeared after enabling alerts
Custom namespace not appearing for login alarm
Understood that metric filters need actual log data first
Generated ConsoleLogin event by logging out and back in
Namespace will appear after log processing completes
Documented as real world learning experience

Real world value:

CloudWatch dashboards are used by every cloud team for monitoring
Billing alarms are mandatory for any AWS account to prevent surprise charges
Console login detection is a critical security monitoring requirement
CloudWatch Logs Insights is used daily by security analysts for investigation
Metric filters transform raw logs into actionable security metrics

Key learnings:

CloudWatch dashboards give single view of entire infrastructure health
Billing alarms should be first thing created in any new AWS account
Metric filters need actual log data before custom namespace appears
Logs Insights allows SQL-like queries on CloudWatch log data
Status check alarms detect EC2 hardware and software failures
All monitoring alarms should notify via SNS for immediate response
S3 storage metrics can be monitored through CloudWatch
